# 1-Intro

This research focuses on understanding how realistic lighting and reflections can be achieved in Unity. While real-time ray tracing provides highly accurate results, it requires specific hardware and is not supported in the Universal Render Pipeline (URP). For this reason, the study examines alternative methods that are accessible to all team members, such as URP's real-time lighting features, light baking techniques and post-processing effects. These approaches make it possible to create visually convincing scenes without relying on high-end GPUs.

To structure the research, the following main question and sub-questions were formulated:

Main question:

- How can realistic reflections and lighting be created in Unity?

Sub-questions:

- What is ray tracing, and how does Unity use it to generate accurate reflections?
- How does URP's lighting system work, and what features does it provide for realism?
- What is light baking and how is it used?
- What is post-processing, and how can it improve lighting realism in URP?

# 2-What is ray tracing, and how does Unity use it to generate accurate reflections?

## 2.1What is raytracing actually?

Ray tracing is a technique used by engines to simulate how light works in real life. It does this by casting a ray from the camera through each pixel. That ray then bounces from object to object depending on the direction it travels, causing reflections. If the ray is blocked by an object, it produces shadows. If it passes through a transparent object, it creates refractions. (Nvidia, n.d.)

There are different types of ray tracing, such as ray casting, path tracing, Bounding Volume Hierarchy (BVH), and denoising filtering.

Ray casting uses single or multiple rays from the camera to detect objects, their color, and the distance between them and the camera.

Path tracing uses hundreds or thousands of rays that bounce between objects many times before reaching the light source to compute realistic lighting and color.

## 2.2 How does raytracing works in unity?

Unity does not support raytracing through traditional render pipeline but through High Definition Render Pipeline (HDRP). Its importance to know that you need an RTX graphic card or RX6000 series(from AMD) and higher to use Raytracing probably.

Assuming that not everyone in our team have the hardware requirements I will search up further for methods to make light realistic using shader-graphs.

# 3-How does URP's lighting system work, and what features does it provide for realism?

Unity's Universal Render Pipeline (URP) provides several lighting tools that make scenes look more realistic. Lights are added as Light components in the scene, and URP supports directional, point, and spot lights for real-time lighting. Area lights exist only for baked lighting, not real-time. Each light can be customized in the Inspector by adjusting its color, intensity, range, and which layers it affects.

URP supports three lighting modes: Baked, Realtime, and Mixed.

Baked lighting precomputes lighting for static objects before the game starts, producing realistic indirect light and improving performance. Realtime lighting updates every frame and is used for dynamic objects. Mixed lighting combines both: direct light from a source is real-time, while indirect light is baked, allowing moving objects to receive correct lighting without a high performance cost.

URP uses a physically based rendering (PBR) workflow. Directional lights behave like sunlight and illuminate the entire scene from one direction. Point and spot lights emit light outward from a source. Realism comes from shadows, indirect lighting, and how materials react to light, not from rays bouncing physically like in ray tracing. URP does not simulate light bouncing automatically instead indirect light comes from baked global illumination and lightmaps.

# 4-What is light baking and how to use it?

In Unity, if baking is not used, static lights must be calculated in real time every time the game runs. To avoid this, Unity offers two pre-calculating methods: lightmaps and light probes.

With lightmap baking, Unity pre-renders how light hits surfaces in the scene so the lighting does not need to be computed during gameplay. When you add or change lights, you must bake again (or enable automatic baking).

## 4.1 How to use baking and lightmapping

When you create a static object, you need to mark it as Static in the Inspector. This tells the engine which objects are not going to move and should be included in the baking process.

To apply a lightmap to your mesh:

 Enable Generate Lightmap UVs in the Model Import Settings.

 Ensure the mesh has a Mesh Renderer or is a Terrain object.

 Mark the object as Contribute GI in the Static menu.

 The object should use a Unity built-in material/shader for best results.

![Afbeelding met schermopname, pc-game, Digitale composities, ComputerspelDoor AI gegenereerde inhoud is mogelijk onjuist.](data:image/png;base64,)You can also use the Lightmap Debugger after enabling [Global Illumination](https://docs.unity3d.com/6000.2/Documentation/Manual/choose-a-lighting-setup.html) in the Lighting settings. The debugger helps you track how the lighting is processed and makes it easier to find lighting issues.

Light probes store lighting information in space instead of on surfaces, unlike lightmaps. They are used to provide indirect lighting for dynamic objects, since baked lighting has a fixed direction and does not automatically update. Light probes "catch" the surrounding baked light and apply it to moving objects. You can use them by adding a Light Probe Group component to your scene.

# 5-What is post-processing and how it can improve lighting realism in URP?

Post-processing refers to the use of full-screen filters and visual effects that are applied to the camera's rendered image before it is displayed on screen. These effects operate on the final image rather than on individual objects or light sources in the scene. According to the documentation, "post-processing is the process of applying full-screen filters and effects to a camera's image buffer before it is displayed on screen" (documentation, n.d.). By applying post-processing effects, developers can enhance the visual quality of a scene and increase the perceived realism.

The Universal Render Pipeline (URP) provides support for a range of [post processing effect](https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/post-processing-effect-availability-reference.html) such as Bloom, Color Grading, Ambient Occlusion, Vignette and Depth of Field. Each of these contributes to realism in a different way. Bloom simulates the natural glow of bright light sources. Ambient Occlusion adds subtle shadowing to creases and corners, making objects appear more grounded. Color Grading allows fine control over contrast and color balance, enabling developers to match the appearance of real cameras or film. Additional effects like Depth of Field further replicate real-world camera behavior by introducing focus and blur.

Compared to using standard URP lighting alone, post-processing can significantly improve visual realism. Normal lighting calculates the physical interaction of light with surfaces, but without post-processing the resulting image may appear flat or clinical. By adding post-processing, the final image gains depth, atmosphere and photographic qualities that are difficult to achieve with lighting alone. This combination of real-time lighting and post-processing effects is essential for achieving high-quality, realistic visuals in URP.

URP uses volumes for post-processing effects. Those can override the scene properties depending on the camera position relative to the other volumes. There are 2 types of volumes global and local. Global does effects the whole camera view while the local effects only the camera when the collider of  the parent game object.

# 6-Conclusion

This research shows that realistic lighting in Unity's Universal Render Pipeline can be achieved effectively without relying on hardware-intensive ray tracing. By combining URP's real-time lighting system with baked lighting techniques such as lightmapping and light probes, it is possible to create scenes that appear natural and visually convincing. Post-processing plays a crucial role in enhancing the final image by adding depth, contrast and camera-like effects that standard lighting alone cannot provide.

Although reflections and advanced ray tracing techniques were not explored in detail due to hardware limitations, the results demonstrate that URP already offers practical and accessible tools for achieving realism. For teams working with limited resources, focusing on post-processing, proper light setup and efficient baking workflows provides a reliable alternative to ray tracing. Future research may look more closely at reflection techniques, such as reflection probes or Shader Graph approaches, to further improve realism in URP without requiring high-end GPUs.
